## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

**Pattern:** Timeout enforcement via `Thread.Abort` → cooperative cancellation with `CancellationTokenSource`.

### Why it breaks

In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is a no-op. You must use cooperative cancellation.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return ExecuteWithTimeout(
            token => work(),  // wrapper for legacy code that ignores the token
            timeout);
    }

    // Preferred overload — work can cooperate with cancellation
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

---

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Guidance |
|---------|----------|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | The `Func<T>` overload can't force-stop uncooperative code. Use the `Func<CancellationToken, T>` overload and call `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside loops. |
| **Leaked `CancellationTokenSource`** | Always wrap in `using`. Leaks timers and callbacks. |
| **Blocking I/O ignores the token** | `Thread.Sleep`, `socket.Read` won't respond. Use async I/O or `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` instead. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it at the orchestration boundary (here, to rethrow as `TimeoutException`). |
| **Truly uncooperative code** | If you can't modify the work (e.g., third-party), move it to a child `Process` and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout. There is no in-process equivalent of the old `Thread.Abort`. |

---

### Usage Example

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// Cooperative work (preferred) — responds to cancellation
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        // ... expensive iteration ...
    }
    return 42;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// Legacy work (fire-and-forget on timeout — thread keeps running!)
var legacy = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SomeLegacyCall(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

> ⚠️ The legacy overload returns on timeout but **cannot kill the background work**. The thread pool task runs to completion (or forever). This is the fundamental trade-off — cooperative cancellation only works if the code cooperates.
